Import lab data

Get to work on that list. Note that there are 9 pages in total of the report. All pages except the last have tables with 8 data columns, preceded on the left by a label column. The last page is the same, but with 1 data column instead of 8.

new <- all %>%
    # split into lines
    lapply( strsplit, split = "\n" ) %>% lapply( "[[", 1L ) %>%
    # replace characters we don't want to deal with here
    lapply( gsub, pattern = "%|/|\\(|\\)", replacement = "" ) %>%
    lapply( gsub, pattern = "< ", replacement = "<" ) %>%
    # split lines into "cells"
    lapply( strsplit, split = " " )

Now bind title text into a single cell. Different for pages 1 to 8 (where we can take the last 8 vector items as data columns because of the table size on those pages)

pg1to8 <- list()
# Collapse everything not in the data (last 8) columns to one coherent text string.
pg1to8 <- lapply( 1:8, function(x) {
    pg1to8[[x]] <- lapply( new[[x]], function(e) {
        c( paste0( head( e, length( e ) - 8L ), collapse = "" ), tail( e, 8L ) )
    } )
} )

Put all pages back into the same list again

pg1to8[[ length(pg1to8) + 1L ]] <- pg9

Bind everything together into a single data table

labResults <- pg1to8 %>%
    # bind column-wise within list items
    lapply( do.call, what = cbind ) %>%
    # bind row-wise between list items
    do.call( what = rbind ) %>%
    as.data.table()

The vast majority of those columns are filled with NAs, so there’s no need to keep those.

sp.soils.coords[ , which( sapply( sp.soils.coords, function(x) all( is.na(x) ) ) ) := NULL ]
glimpse( sp.soils.coords )

The columns “type” and “comment” are of no interest to us here, so we’ll discard them too.

sp.soils.coords[ , c( "type", "comment" ) := NULL ]
glimpse( sp.soils.coords )

Now we can convert the ident column to match the format of the data we have. These are all “SP” sites, so we’ll add that too all rows.

sp.soils.coords[ , ident := ident %>%
                     stringLength( length.out = 2L, which = "tail", fill = "0" )
                 %>% paste0( "SP", . )
                 ]
unique( sp.soils.coords$ident )

Confirm that all sites have a match in the main dataset

View the data on a map

Now that we’ve got spatial coordinates, we can have a look at the data on a map.

sp.map <- ggmap::get_map( location = c( lon = mean( all$long, na.rm = T ), lat = mean( all$lat, na.rm = T ) ), 
                           zoom = 14 )

We’re not looking to analyse the dataset as a whole here, but we can choose a couple of random variables to look at.

ggmap( sp.map ) + 
    geom_point( data = all, aes( x = long, y = lat, size = as.numeric( OrganicCarbon ) ), col = "red" ) +
    ggtitle( "Organic Carbon results. CSBP 2017-01." )

ggmap( sp.map ) + 
    geom_point( data = all, aes( x = long, y = lat, size = as.numeric( NitrateNitrogenmgKg ) ), col = "red" ) +
    ggtitle( "Nitrate Nitrogen. CSBP 2017-01." )

ggmap( sp.map ) + 
    geom_point( data = all, aes( x = long, y = lat, size = as.numeric( pHLevelH2OpH ) ), col = "red" ) +
    ggtitle( "H2O pH. CSBP 2017-01." )
